	<text>
		<body>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_landwirt_margot">Maria Landwirt</persName> Testimony (doc. 301/1538)</p>
			<p>Original, manuscript, 2 pages, 210 x 295 mm, Polish language</p>
			<p><pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3011538_01.jpg"/>
				<placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-0" type="camp">Oświęcim [Auschwitz]</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-42" type="camp">Bergen-Belsen</placeName>, <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2955168/aschersleben.html">Aschersleben</placeName></p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_landwirt_margot">Maria Landwirt</persName> born <date when="1927-03-07">7.3.1927</date> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2803138/antwerpen.html">Antwerp</placeName>. Raised in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/798544/republic-of-poland.html">Poland</placeName>. The <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1080">war</term> found her in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3094802/krakow.html">Cracow</placeName>. On <date when="1943-03-20">March 20</date>, she found
				herself [in] the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term>; she was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-115" type="subject">deported</term>; on <date when="1943-03-12">March 12,
					1943</date>, she got into the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-555" type="camp"
					>Płaszów</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term>. She was told about the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">hanging</term> of two 20-year old <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825">girls</term> for leaving the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term> and going to the city without permits,
				which made a strong impression on her. Besides, nothing bad happened to her personally there. On <date when="1944-08-06">August 6,
					1944</date> she was sent to <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-0" type="camp"
				>Oświęcim</placeName>. 135 people rode in a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">cattle
					car</term> with her; at the station the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject"
					>children</term> and the elderly were segregated. Then they were all taken in front of the baths and there, in the presence of
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-485" type="subject">KP-men</term>, <note type="gloss">KP-men,
					kapomen – a kapo (an inmate functionary)</note> all <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825"
					type="subject">women</term> had to strip naked; then they were all taken to a shed, where they waited for a bath all night, naked,
				without <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>. For the slightest movement they
				were beaten with crops at random by the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-485" type="subject"
					>kapomen</term>. At daybreak they went to the baths in groups; they were deprived of all their belongings; they were shaved, their
				heads, armpits and nether regions. They were shaved by men and women. Wet after the bath, they were chucked out into a room (most
				women had been deprived of their <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">shoes</term>),
				where were thrown some <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">rags</term> which they put on
				wet bodies. They were convinced they were going to a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501" type="subject"
					>crematory</term>, but they were taken to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject"
					>camp</term>. During her stay in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term>
				it once happened that a certain <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_hungarians">Hungarian</term>
				<term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825">woman</term> overslept and didn’t report for <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject">roll call</term>. A search began and when they found
				her the <foreign xml:lang="de">Lagerführer</foreign> laid her on the ground and kept kicking and beating her, in full view of
				everybody, until she expired. The most horrible thing were <q><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411"
						type="subject">selections</term></q>. That’s when the <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-140" type="subject">doctor</term>
				<persName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_pers-000272">Mengele</persName>
				<note type="gloss">In the text: Mengerle</note> appeared. He arranged all the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term>, stripped naked, into rows and removed
				those he didn’t like from the rows. Those <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject"
					>women</term> were then closed for 24 hours in small rooms, duty rooms, without <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>, and after that a truck came and took them
				to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501" type="subject">crematory</term> in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2" type="camp">Brzezinka</placeName>
				<note type="gloss">In the text: in Brzezinki</note> b. There were usually about 100 of such victims. We lived in the constant fear of
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">death</term>.</p>
			<p>On <date when="1944-10-31">October 31, 1944</date>, 3000 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825"
					type="subject">women</term> were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-115" type="subject">sent</term>
				from <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-0" type="camp">Oświęcim</placeName>
				<pb n="2" facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3011538_02.jpg"/> to <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-42" type="camp"
					>Bergen-Belsen</placeName>. We stood outdoors throughout the night in our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">rags</term>, waiting for a bath. After the bath
				there was another <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">selection</term>. The elderly,
				slim or pregnant <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term>, as well as <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term> were destined for <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">death</term> and immediately separated. The rest was
				given better <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">clothes</term> for the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">transport</term>. There rode 65 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term> in each <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">cattle car</term>. They were given <q>sufficient</q>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> for the journey for it consisted of one
				loaf of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">bread</term>, 10 dkg of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">margarine</term> and 15 dkg of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">sausage</term> per head for the three days. They
				relieved nature in the closed car. After three days they arrived in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-42" type="camp">Bergen-Belsen</placeName>. They reported for <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject">roll call</term>, where they were kept for 5 hours,
				after which they were taken to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">tents</term>, where
				there was a bit of damp straw and 2 thin blankets per each. They washed outdoors in <date when="1945-12">December</date>, at water
				taps, usually at dawn.</p>
			<p>One day the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">tents</term> were torn away by a storm,
				so the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">prisoners</term> were moved to the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term> kitchen, where those 1500 <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term> stayed squeezed for 4 days. Then they
				were moved to the <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837">barracks</term> left by <term
					type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_americans">American</term> citizens, where it was more bearable while in terms of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term>, it was disastrous as they were sometimes
				given nothing for 24 hours. That depended on the Sturmmann’s <note type="gloss">SS-Sturmmann – a military rank in the SS (the
					equivalent of Corporal)</note> 2 disposition. After 3 pm it was dark, so they usually went to sleep. There was no work and they
				were afflicted by idleness and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569" type="subject">hunger</term>. After
				three months they took us to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2955168/aschersleben.html">Aschersleben</placeName> (near
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2874545/magdeburg.html">Magdeburg</placeName>). Our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> consisted in testing pipes for airplanes.
				We <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-253">sabotaged</term> that work with the knowledge of
				the <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term> foreman <persName ref="#ehri_et_riesener_otto">Otto
					Riesener</persName>. There it was bearable, but on <date when="1945-04-12">April 12</date> we were sent towards<placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-177" type="camp">Dachau</placeName>. It turned out, however, that the road
				we were supposed to take was occupied. In <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2803891/zoerbig.html">Zörbig</placeName>, <note
					place="bottom">In the text: Zerbig</note> it turned out that the <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_americans"
					>Americans</term> were 30 km away from <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2879139/leipzig.html">Leipzig</placeName>, so part
				of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS men</term> fled and the rest rode with the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">prisoners</term> on carts. Part of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">fled</term> to the forest and that’s where they
				waited until the <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_americans">American</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">army</term> came on <date when="1945-04-15">April
					15, 1945</date>.</p>
			<p><placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3094802/krakow.html">Cracow</placeName>, <date when="1945-08-27">August 27, 1945</date></p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_landwirt_margot">Margoth Landwirth</persName></p>
			<p>Written down by <persName ref="#ehri_et_eichhornowa_laura">Dr Laura Eichhornowa</persName></p>
